\begin_body

\begin_layout Section
Formulas and Mathematical Detail
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 test portfolios, 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{t}^{e}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 by 1) which are assumed to be excess returns (zero-investment portfolios)
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 factors, 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{t}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 by 1).
 For each there are 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 observations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Linear Factor Model for Traded Factors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
This model is a Seemingly Unrelated Regression (SUR).
 All models share the same regressors so that the model for test portfolio
 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r_{it}^{e}=\alpha_{i}+\beta_{i}f_{t}+\epsilon_{it}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Inference is based on the sandwich covariance estimator 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{\Sigma}=\left(T-df\right)^{-1}A^{-1}BA^{-1}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{A}=I_{N}\otimes\Sigma_{\left[1\:f^{\prime}\right]}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Sigma_{\left[1\:f^{\prime}\right]}=T^{-1}\sum_{t=1}^{T}\tilde{f}_{t}\tilde{f}_{t}^{\prime}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{f}_{t}=\left(1\:f^{\prime}\right)^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 is the set of factor returns augmented with a constant.
 Define the stacked vector of scores
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s_{t}=\left[\epsilon_{t}\otimes\tilde{f}_{t}^{\prime}\right].
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
If the heteroskedasticity robust estimator is used, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{B}=T^{-1}\sum_{t=1}^{T}s_{t}s_{t}^{\prime}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
If the HAC estiamtor is used, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\hat{B} & =T^{-1}\left\{ \hat{\Gamma}_{0}+\sum_{i=1}^{bw}K\left(i,bw\right)\left(\hat{\Gamma}_{i}+\hat{\Gamma}_{i}^{\prime}\right)\right\} \\
\hat{\Gamma}_{j} & =\sum_{t=j+1}^{T}s_{t}s_{t-j}^{\prime}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
where 
\begin_inset Formula $K\left(i,bw\right)$
\end_inset

 is a kernel weighting function and 
\begin_inset Formula $bw$
\end_inset

 is the bandwidth.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The J statistic
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
The J statistic is implemented as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
J=\hat{\alpha}^{\prime}\hat{\Sigma}_{\alpha}^{-1}\hat{\alpha}^{\prime}\sim\chi_{N}^{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\Sigma}_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 consists of rows and columns
\begin_inset Formula $1,(k+1)+1,2(k+1)+1,\ldots$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\Sigma}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Linear Factor Model for Non-traded Factors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When factors are not traded, the SUR approach cannot be used since the expected
 value of the factor is not equal to its risk premium.
 One solution is to use a 2-step estimator.
 The first step regresses the test portfolio returns on the factors and
 a (throw-away) constant.
 This constant is included only to demean the factors to compute the correct
 factor loadings.
 The second stage then uses the estimated factor loadings and the average
 portfolio returns to estimate the risk premia.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first stage regressions are virtually identical to the SUR regressions
 except the constant is no longer 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r_{it}^{e}=c_{i}+\beta_{i}f_{t}+\epsilon_{it}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second stage regression then uses the estimated coefficients as regressors
 to estimate the risk premia, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bar{r}_{i}^{e}=\hat{\beta}\lambda+\eta_{i}.
\]

\end_inset

Note that the residual from this regression
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\eta}_{i}=\hat{\alpha}_{i}$
\end_inset

, the excess compensation test portfolio 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 is generating.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Inference is conducted by treating this as a 3-step GMM problem where the
 first two steps were jsut described and the third estimated the model 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\alpha}$
\end_inset

.
 The moment conditions corresponding to the FOC of these three steps are
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g_{t}=\left[\begin{array}{c}
\epsilon_{t}\otimes\left[1\,f_{t}^{\prime}\right]^{\prime}\\
\beta^{\prime}\left(r_{t}-\beta\lambda\right)\\
r_{t}-\beta\lambda-\alpha
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{it}=r_{it}^{e}-c_{i}-\beta_{i}f_{t}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{t}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 by 1, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 by 1, 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{t}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 by 1, 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{t}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 by 1 and
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 by 1.
 Inference is based on 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{\Sigma}=T^{-1}G^{-1}S\left(G^{-1}\right)^{\prime}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
where the Jacobian 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is estimated by 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
r_{1t}-a_{1}-\beta_{1}f_{t}\\
\left(r_{1t}-a_{1}-\beta_{1}f_{t}\right)f_{t}\\
r_{2t}-a_{2}-\beta_{2}f_{t}\\
\left(r_{2t}-a_{2}-\beta_{2}f_{t}\right)f_{t}\\
\beta^{\prime}\left(r_{t}-\beta\lambda\right)\\
r_{1t}-\beta_{1}\lambda-\alpha_{1}\\
r_{2t}-\beta_{2}\lambda-\alpha_{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Parameters of interest are 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{2}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=\mu_{r}-\beta^{\prime}\lambda$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{ccccccc}
1 & f_{t} & 0 & 0 & 0 & 0 & 0\\
f_{t} & f_{t}^{2} & 0 & 0 & 0 & 0 & 0\\
0 & 0 & 1 & f_{t} & 0 & 0 & 0\\
0 & 0 & f_{t} & f_{t}^{2} & 0 & 0 & 0\\
0 & r_{t}-2\beta_{1}\lambda & 0 & r_{t}-2\beta_{2}\lambda & \beta_{1}^{2}+\beta_{2}^{2} & 0 & 0\\
0 & -\lambda & 0 & 0 & -\beta_{1} & 1 & 0\\
0 & 0 & 0 & -\lambda & -\beta_{2} & 0 & 1
\end{array}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\epsilon_{t}\\
\epsilon_{t}\otimes f_{t}\\
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{G}=-\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
I_{N}\otimes\Sigma_{\left[1\,f\right]} & 0 & 0\\
G_{21} & \beta^{\prime}\beta & 0\\
I_{N}\otimes\left[0\ \lambda\right] & \beta & I_{N}
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
The block 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{21}$
\end_inset

is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G_{21}=\left[G_{21,1}\ G_{21,2}\:\ldots\ G_{21,N}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G_{21,i}=\left[0_{K\times1}\:\left(\beta_{i}^{\prime}\lambda^{\prime}-E_{T}\left[u_{it}\right]I_{K}\right)\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
where expectations are replaced by sample averaged.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is an estimator of the scores and its form is identical to either the heteroske
dasticity consistent estimator or the HAC estimator in the previous section.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The J statistic
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The J statistic is virtually identical except that it has a difference distribut
ion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
J=\hat{\alpha}^{\prime}\hat{\Sigma}_{\alpha}^{-1}\hat{\alpha}^{\prime}\sim\chi_{N-K}^{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
The loss of degrees of freedom is obvious since 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\alpha}=\hat{\eta}$
\end_inset

 which are regression residuals from a regression of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 average returns on 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 factor loadings.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\Sigma}_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 is the bottom right block of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\Sigma}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G_{31}=\left[G_{31,1}\ G_{31,2}\ \ldots G_{31,N}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G_{31,i}=\left[0_{N\times1}\ e_{i}\otimes\lambda\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
where 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}$
\end_inset

is a 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 by 1 vector of 0 except in location 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 which is 1 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{i}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Verification with 3 assets and 2 factors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
-\left[\begin{array}{c}
r_{1t}-a_{1}-\beta_{11}f_{1t}-\beta_{12}f_{2t}\\
\left(r_{1t}-a_{1}-\beta_{11}f_{1t}-\beta_{12}f_{2t}\right)f_{1t}\\
\left(r_{1t}-a_{1}-\beta_{11}f_{1t}-\beta_{12}f_{2t}\right)f_{2t}\\
r_{2t}-a_{2}-\beta_{21}f_{1t}-\beta_{22}f_{2t}\\
\left(r_{2t}-a_{2}-\beta_{21}f_{1t}-\beta_{22}f_{2t}\right)f_{1t}\\
\left(r_{2t}-a_{2}-\beta_{21}f_{1t}-\beta_{22}f_{2t}\right)f_{2t}\\
r_{3t}-a_{3}-\beta_{31}f_{1t}-\beta_{32}f_{2t}\\
\left(r_{3t}-a_{3}-\beta_{31}f_{1t}-\beta_{32}f_{3t}\right)f_{1t}\\
\left(r_{3t}-a_{3}-\beta_{31}f_{1t}-\beta_{32}f_{3t}\right)f_{2t}\\
\sum_{i=1}^{3}\beta_{i1}\left(r_{it}-\beta_{i1}\lambda_{1}-\beta_{i2}\lambda_{2}\right)\\
\sum_{i=1}^{3}\beta_{i2}\left(r_{it}-\beta_{i1}\lambda_{1}-\beta_{i2}\lambda_{2}\right)\\
r_{1t}-\beta_{11}\lambda_{1}-\beta_{12}\lambda_{2}-\alpha_{1}\\
r_{2t}-\beta_{21}\lambda_{1}-\beta_{22}\lambda_{2}-\alpha_{2}\\
r_{3t}-\beta_{31}\lambda_{1}-\beta_{32}\lambda_{2}-\alpha_{3}
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

